* At the emitter there is the signal sent to the base. Example of negative feedback.
* Common collector configuration (also known as Emitter-Follower)
* Sizing:\n \n1) Set Vout quiescent point at 7 V\n2) Set Ie = 2 mA -> Re = R1 = 7/2 mA = 3.5k ohm\n3) Ib = Ie/(beta+1) = 8.7 uA approximately with beta=230\n4) Vbase = 7 + 0.6 = 7.6 V -> Rb = R2 = (12-7.6)/8.7uA = 505k ohm\n5) Cap should offer very low impedance at signal frequency 100kHz ->\nXc = 1/(2*pi*f*C) for instance 10m Ohm -> C = 1/(2*pi*f*0.01)=159 uF\n \nExpected gain: 0.996 -> 20*log10(0.996) = -34 mdB -> almost 1
.ac dec 100 1 1Meg
* Sizing same as above except R4 and R5 sizing:\n \n1) Set Vout quiescent point at 7 V\n2) Set Ie = 2 mA -> Re = R3 = 7/2 mA = 3.5k ohm\n3) Ib = Ie/(beta+1) = 8.7 uA approximately with beta=230\n4) Vbase = 7 + 0.6 = 7.6 V\nTotal current through R4 set 10* Ib = 87 uA\nR4 = (12-7.6)/87u=50.6k ohm\na=(7.6/12)=R5/(R5+R4) -> R5 = R4*a/(1-a)=86.15k \n5) Cap should offer very low impedance at signal frequency 100kHz ->\nXc = 1/(2*pi*f*C) for instance 10m Ohm -> C = 1/(2*pi*f*0.01)=159 uF\n \nOver previous configuration\nAdvantage: use lower value resistors for biasing\nDisadvantage: use 2 resistors for biasing\n \nExpected gain: 0.996 -> 20*log10(0.996) = -34 mdB -> almost 1
